Euboea itself also is sundered from Boeotia by so moderate a channcl, the Euripus, that it is joined to the mainland by a bridge. At the south end it has two marked promontories, Capo Mandili point- ing towards Attica and Kavo Doro towards the Dardanellcs3 at the north it has Cape Lithadha. Its breadth nowhere exceeds 40 miles and nowhere contracts below two miles3 its length stretches along the whole of Boeotia from Attica to Thessaly and measures 150 miles, while its circumference is 365 miles. At its south-easternmost point, its distance from the Dardanelles is 225 miles. Its notable cities were formerly Pyrrha, Porthmos, Nesos, Cerin- thos‚ Oreus, Dium, Acdepsos‚ Ocha and Oechalia3 those now noteworthy are Chalcis (opposite which on the mainland is Aulis), Geraestus‚ Eretria, Carystus, Oritanum and Artemisium, as well as the Spring of Arethusa, thc river Lelantus and the warm springs known as the Hellop1 ie Euboea is, however still better known for the marble of Carystus.
